\subsection*{Problem 6-25}
\textbf{Statement:}\\
Re-solve the cylindrical bar magnet problem of Example 6-9, using the equivalent magnetization current density concept.

\textbf{Solution:}\\
For a cylinder (\(b,L\)) with \(\mathbf{M}=a_zM_0\):
\[ \mathbf{J}_m=\nabla\times\mathbf{M}=0, \quad \mathbf{K}_m=\mathbf{M}\times a_r =M_0\,a_\phi. \]
Treating the side wall as a solenoidal surface current \(K_m=M_0\), the on-axis field at \(z\) is
\[ B_z(z) =\frac{\mu_0 M_0 b^2}{2}\Bigl[ \frac{1}{\bigl(b^2+(z+\tfrac L2)^2\bigr)^{3/2}} -\frac{1}{\bigl(b^2+(z-\tfrac L2)^2\bigr)^{3/2}} \Bigr], \]
which reproduces Example 6-9.

