\section*{Solutions to Problems 6-26 through 6-30}

\subsection*{Problem 6-26}
\textbf{Statement:}\\
A ferromagnetic sphere of radius \(b\) is magnetized uniformly with a magnetization \(\mathbf{M}=a_zM_0\).  
Determine the equivalent magnetization current densities \(J_m\) and \(K_m\), and find the magnetic flux density at the center of the sphere.

\textbf{Solution:}\\
Uniform magnetization \(\mathbf{M}=M_0\,a_z\) gives
\[ \mathbf{J}_m=\nabla\times\mathbf{M}=0, \qquad \mathbf{K}_m=\mathbf{M}\times\hat n =M_0\,a_z\times a_r =M_0\sin\!\theta\,a_\phi. \]
Inside a uniformly magnetized sphere the field is uniform:
\[ \mathbf{B} =\frac{2}{3}\,\mu_0\mathbf{M} =\frac{2}{3}\,\mu_0M_0\,a_z. \]

