\subsection*{Problem 6-30}
\textbf{Statement:}\\
Prove that \(\nabla\times H = J\) leads to the boundary condition for \(H\) at an interface between two media,
\[ \hat n\times(\mathbf{H}_2-\mathbf{H}_1)=\mathbf{J}_s. \]

\textbf{Solution:}\\
Integrate \(\nabla\times\mathbf{H}=\mathbf{J}\) over a rectangular loop straddling the interface and apply Stokes’ theorem:
\[ \oint\mathbf{H}\cdot d\mathbf{l} =\iint\mathbf{J}\cdot d\mathbf{S}. \]
As the loop height shrinks to zero, only the tangential components on either side remain:
\[ (\mathbf{H}_2)_t-(\mathbf{H}_1)_t =\mathbf{J}_s\times\hat n, \]
or equivalently
\(\hat n\times(\mathbf{H}_2-\mathbf{H}_1)=\mathbf{J}_s\).

