\subsection*{Problem 6-35}
\textbf{Statement:}\\
Determine the self‐inductance of a toroidal coil of \(N\) turns on an air frame with mean radius \(r_0\) and circular cross‐section of radius \(b\).  Obtain an approximate expression for \(b\ll r_0\).

\textbf{Solution:}\\
The exact inductance is
\[ L =\frac{\mu_0N^2}{2\pi} \int_{r_0-b}^{\,r_0+b}\frac{A(r)}{r}\,dr, \]
where \(A(r)\) is the local cross‐sectional area.  For \(b\ll r_0\) one may replace \(A(r)\) by its total area \(S=\pi b^2\) at \(r=r_0\), yielding
\[ L\approx\frac{\mu_0N^2\,S}{2\pi\,r_0} =\frac{\mu_0N^2b^2}{2r_0}. \]

[...]

\subsection*{Problem 6-36}
\textbf{Statement:}\\
Refer to Example 6-16. Determine the inductance per unit length of the air coaxial transmission line assuming that its outer conductor is not very thin but is of a thickness \(d\).

\textbf{Solution:}\\
Let the inner conductor radius be \(a\), the outer conductor inner radius \(b\), and its thickness \(d\). The return current \(-I\) is uniformly distributed over the cross‐section of the cylindrical shell \(b<r<b+d\). By Ampère’s law:
\[ B_\phi(r)=
\begin{cases}
\displaystyle \frac{\mu_0 I}{2\pi r}, & a<r<b,\\[8pt]
\displaystyle \frac{\mu_0 I_{\rm enc}(r)}{2\pi r}
=\frac{\mu_0 I}{2\pi r}\;\frac{(b+d)^2 - r^2}{(b+d)^2 - b^2}, 
& b<r<b+d,\\[8pt]
0,&r>b+d.
\end{cases}
\]
where 
\(\displaystyle I_{\rm enc}(r)=I\Bigl[1-\frac{\pi(r^2-b^2)}{\pi\bigl((b+d)^2-b^2\bigr)}\Bigr]\).
The flux linkage per unit length is
\[ \lambda=\int_a^b B_\phi(r)\,dr + \int_b^{b+d} B_\phi(r)\,dr
=\frac{\mu_0 I}{2\pi}\Biggl[
\underbrace{\ln\frac{b}{a}}_{(1)}
+\underbrace{\frac{(b+d)^2}{(b+d)^2-b^2}\ln\frac{b+d}{b}-\frac12}_{(2)}
\Biggr].
\]
Hence the inductance per unit length is
\[ L'=\frac{\lambda}{I}
=\frac{\mu_0}{2\pi}\Biggl[
\ln\frac{b}{a}
+\frac{(b+d)^2}{(b+d)^2-b^2}\ln\frac{b+d}{b}-\frac12
\Biggr].
\]

[...]

\subsection*{Problem 6-40}
\textbf{Statement:}\\
Find the mutual inductance between two coplanar rectangular loops with parallel sides, as shown in Fig.~6-50. Assume that \(h_1\gg h_2\) and \(h_2>w_2>d\).

\textbf{Solution:}\\
Label the sides of the larger loop \(h_1\) (parallel to the smaller’s \(h_2\)) and width \(w_1\), and similarly \(h_2,w_2\) for the smaller. The mutual inductance is given by the sum over four side‐to‐side interactions:
\[ \boxed{
M
=\frac{\mu_0}{4\pi}\sum_{i=1}^2\sum_{j=1}^2
(-1)^{i+j}\,
\ell_i\,\ln\frac{r_{i j}^+}{r_{i j}^-}
},
\]
where \(\ell_i\) is the length of the \(i\)-th side and \(r_{ij}^\pm\) are the distances from its ends to the ends of the \(j\)-th side of the other loop. In the limit \(h_1\gg h_2\), this simplifies to
\[ M\approx\frac{\mu_0h_2}{2\pi}
\ln\!\frac{d+w_2}{d}\,.
\]

